---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Factoring Calculator | Find All Factors of Any Number",
  description: "Instantly find all factors, prime factorization, and factor pairs of any integer. Perfect for math students and developers looking for a fast, simple...",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a factor in math?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A factor is a whole number that divides completely into another number without leaving a remainder. For example, the factors of 12 are 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 12."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a prime number?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A prime number is a whole number greater than 1 whose only divisors are 1 and itself. Examples include 2, 3, 5, 7, and 11. If our calculator returns only two factors for a number, that number is prime."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does the factoring calculator work?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Our calculator tests all integers from 1 up to the square root of your input. When it finds a number that divides your input evenly, it records both the divisor and the quotient as factors, ensuring a complete and mathematically accurate list."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can this calculator factor negative numbers?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Mathematically, the factors of a negative integer are the same as its positive counterpart, but with both positive and negative variations. For simplicity, this tool calculates the absolute positive factors of the integer provided."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are factor pairs?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Factor pairs are two integers that, when multiplied together, equal the original number. For example, the factor pairs of 10 are (1, 10) and (2, 5)."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Silicon Based"
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="sendnerds" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://photonbuilder.com/sendnerds/factoring-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Factoring Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Enter any integer to instantly calculate all of its factors, factor pairs, and determine if it is a prime number.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="number-input">Enter an integer to factor</label>
        <input type="number" id="number-input" value="12" step="1" aria-describedby="number-error">
        <span class="error-message" id="number-error">Please enter a valid non-zero integer. Max value: 999,999,999.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="result-section" id="result-section">
        <div style="text-align: center;">
          <div id="prime-indicator" class="prime-badge composite">Composite Number</div>
        </div>

        <div class="factors-grid">
          <div class="factors-card">
            <h3 id="factor-count-title">Factors of 12 (6 total)</h3>
            <div class="factor-list" id="factor-list">
              <!-- Factors injected here -->
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="factors-card">
            <h3>Factor Pairs</h3>
            <div class="pair-list" id="pair-list">
              <!-- Pairs injected here -->
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>How to Use the Factoring Calculator</h2>
      <p>Factoring is one of the most fundamental operations in mathematics, serving as the building block for everything from basic middle-school arithmetic to advanced cryptography algorithms used in computer science. Our factoring calculator is built to immediately process any given integer and break it down into its constituent parts: a comprehensive list of its factors, distinct factor pairs, and an automated check for prime or composite status.</p>

      <p>To use the calculator, simply type any integer into the input field above. The calculator listens to your input in real time—there is no need to click a submit button. As you type, the tool dynamically recalculates the output, rendering the factor pills and a multiplied list of factor pairs instantly.</p>

      <h3>What Are Factors and Prime Factorization?</h3>
      <p>A <strong>factor</strong> is simply a number that divides into another number evenly, leaving a remainder of zero. For instance, if you input the number 24, the calculator returns 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, and 24. This is because dividing 24 by any of these numbers results in a perfect integer.</p>

      <p>An extension of this concept is finding a number's <strong>prime factorization</strong>. Prime factorization is the process of breaking down a composite number into a set of prime numbers that, when multiplied together, yield the original number. While our calculator currently outputs all whole factors, understanding prime factors is critical for developers, especially when designing hash functions or working with RSA encryption where massive semi-prime numbers secure web traffic.</p>

      <h3>The Algorithm: How We Find Factors Fast</h3>
      <p>You might wonder how the calculator can process numbers as large as 999,999,999 instantly without crashing your browser. The secret lies in a highly optimized mathematical algorithm that avoids brute-forcing every single number.</p>

      <p>Instead of testing every integer from 1 all the way up to your target number <em>n</em> (which would require a billion operations for an input of 1,000,000,000), the calculator only tests numbers up to the <strong>square root of n</strong>. Mathematically, factors always occur in pairs. If <em>a &times; b = n</em>, then one of those numbers must be less than or equal to the square root of <em>n</em>. When our script finds the smaller factor <em>a</em>, it simply divides <em>n / a</em> to instantly discover the larger factor <em>b</em>.</p>

      <p>This simple algorithmic optimization drastically reduces the time complexity from O(n) to O(&radic;n), making the calculation imperceptible to the human eye.</p>

      <h3>Understanding Prime vs. Composite Numbers</h3>
      <p>Our factoring tool automatically labels your input as either Prime, Composite, or Neither. Here is what those designations mean mathematically:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Prime Numbers:</strong> A prime number is any whole number strictly greater than 1 that has exactly two distinct factors: 1 and the number itself. If you type in 17, you will notice the only factors are 1 and 17, triggering the green Prime badge.</li>
        <li><strong>Composite Numbers:</strong> A composite number is any whole number greater than 1 that has more than two distinct factors. Most numbers you encounter (like 10, 15, or 100) are composite.</li>
        <li><strong>Neither:</strong> The numbers 0 and 1 occupy a special place in number theory. The number 1 is not considered prime because it does not have <em>two distinct</em> factors (it only has itself). Thus, our tool correctly labels the number 1 as neither.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Common Uses for Factoring</h3>
      <p>Factoring isn't just a classroom exercise. It has highly practical applications across engineering and finance. Developers frequently use factoring logic when calculating screen aspect ratios, establishing grid systems in CSS, or optimizing loop iterations. Meanwhile, dealing with variables over time is an exercise in compounding math. If you are interested in how numbers compound and affect financial health, explore how compounding works in financial calculators to see math in action.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a factor in math?</summary>
        <p>A factor is a whole number that divides completely into another number without leaving a remainder. For example, the factors of 12 are 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 12.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a prime number?</summary>
        <p>A prime number is a whole number greater than 1 whose only divisors are 1 and itself. Examples include 2, 3, 5, 7, and 11. If our calculator returns exactly two factors for a given input, that number is prime.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does the factoring calculator work?</summary>
        <p>Our calculator algorithm tests all integers from 1 up to the square root of your input. When it finds a number that divides your input evenly (with a remainder of zero), it records both the divisor and the resulting quotient as factors, ensuring a complete list with O(&radic;n) performance.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can this calculator factor negative numbers?</summary>
        <p>Mathematically, the factors of a negative integer are the same as its positive counterpart, but with both positive and negative variations. For simplicity and clarity, this specific tool converts your input to its absolute value and calculates the absolute positive factors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are factor pairs?</summary>
        <p>Factor pairs are two specific integers that, when multiplied together, equal the original starting number. For example, the factor pairs of 10 are (1, 10) and (2, 5).</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const numberInput = document.getElementById('number-input');
      const errorMsg = document.getElementById('number-error');
      const resultSection = document.getElementById('result-section');
      const primeIndicator = document.getElementById('prime-indicator');
      const factorCountTitle = document.getElementById('factor-count-title');
      const factorList = document.getElementById('factor-list');
      const pairList = document.getElementById('pair-list');

      const MAX_SAFE_VAL = 999999999; // Cap to prevent browser hang on very large numbers

      const calculateFactors = () => {
        const rawVal = numberInput.value;
        const num = parseInt(rawVal, 10);

        // Reset state
        numberInput.classList.remove('error');
        errorMsg.style.display = 'none';
        resultSection.classList.remove('visible');

        // Validation
        if (!rawVal || isNaN(num) || num === 0 || !Number.isInteger(parseFloat(rawVal))) {
          numberInput.classList.add('error');
          errorMsg.textContent = "Please enter a valid non-zero integer.";
          errorMsg.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        if (Math.abs(num) > MAX_SAFE_VAL) {
          numberInput.classList.add('error');
          errorMsg.textContent = `Number is too large. Max allowed is ${MAX_SAFE_VAL.toLocaleString()}.`;
          errorMsg.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        const absNum = Math.abs(num);
        const factors = [];
        const pairs = [];
        const limit = Math.floor(Math.sqrt(absNum));

        for (let i = 1; i <= limit; i++) {
          if (absNum % i === 0) {
            factors.push(i);
            const pair = absNum / i;
            if (i !== pair) {
              factors.push(pair);
            }
            pairs.push({ a: i, b: pair });
          }
        }

        factors.sort((a, b) => a - b);

        // Render UI
        const isPrime = absNum > 1 && factors.length === 2;

        if (absNum === 1) {
          primeIndicator.textContent = "Neither Prime Nor Composite";
          primeIndicator.className = "prime-badge composite";
        } else if (isPrime) {
          primeIndicator.textContent = "Prime Number";
          primeIndicator.className = "prime-badge"; // Green style
        } else {
          primeIndicator.textContent = "Composite Number";
          primeIndicator.className = "prime-badge composite"; // Blue style
        }

        factorCountTitle.textContent = `Factors of ${num} (${factors.length} total)`;

        factorList.innerHTML = factors.map(f => `<span class="factor-pill">${f}</span>`).join('');

        pairList.innerHTML = pairs.map(p => `
          <div class="pair-row">
            <span>${p.a}</span>
            <span>&times;</span>
            <span>${p.b}</span>
          </div>
        `).join('');

        resultSection.classList.add('visible');
      };

      numberInput.addEventListener('input', calculateFactors);

      // Initial calculation
      calculateFactors();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .input-group { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; max-width: 400px; margin: 0 auto; text-align: center; }
    label { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-primary); }

    input { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1.25rem; font-family: monospace; text-align: center; }
    input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

    .error-message { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.25rem; display: none; }
    input.error { border-color: #ef4444; }

    .result-section { margin-top: 2rem; display: none; }
    .result-section.visible { display: block; }

    .prime-badge { display: inline-block; background: rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.1); color: #22c55e; padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-radius: 9999px; font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; border: 1px solid rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.2); }
    .prime-badge.composite { background: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.1); color: #3b82f6; border-color: rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.2); }

    .factors-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; }
    @media (min-width: 600px) { .factors-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } }

    .factors-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 5%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; }
    .factors-card h3 { margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--text-primary); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .factor-list { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .factor-pill { background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.4rem 0.8rem; border-radius: 6px; font-family: monospace; font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--accent-color); font-weight: 600; }

    .pair-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .pair-row { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; background: var(--bg-color); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.5rem 1rem; border-radius: 6px; font-family: monospace; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .pair-row span { color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 600; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; color: var(--text-primary); list-style: none; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; }
    .faq-section summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
    .faq-section summary::after { content: '+'; font-size: 1.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); line-height: 1; transition: transform 0.2s; }
    .faq-section details[open] summary::after { content: '−'; transform: rotate(180deg); }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }

    .explainer { margin: 3rem 0; }
    .explainer h2 { color: var(--accent-color); margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
    .explainer h3 { color: var(--text-primary); margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>